I used to love to sleep. Before I had children I could sleep for hours and hours and through any kind of noise...thunderstorm, phone ringing, maybe even a siren. There is a reason why a woman is pregnant for 9 full months, to get ready for the lack of uninterrupted sleep. Sure, in the first trimester I was tired all the time and slept like a log, however, by the last trimester I had to wake up just to turn plus I had to go to the bathroom 1,000 times. I suppose this was my body getting ready for the fragmented sleep I would endure after giving birth.

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/nancys-world/files/2015/08/sleep7.png"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-1757" alt="sleep7" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/nancys-world/files/2015/08/sleep7-300x210.png" width="270" height="189" /></a>Once my children were born, I slept so lightly that I could actually hear my children's dreams...or at least it felt like that. I could hear every cry when they were infants and as they grew older and went out with friends, I was not able to fall into a deeper sleep until they were safely home.

Now my children are grown and live out of the house. One would think that a great sleep would be easily remembered and conquered, like riding a bicycle, however, there are too many obstacles--can you say menopause?

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/nancys-world/files/2015/08/sleep-overrated.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-1756 alignright" alt="sleep overrated" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/nancys-world/files/2015/08/sleep-overrated-257x300.jpg" width="154" height="180" /></a>Between the hot flashes and the waiting for the hot flashes plus my nightly exercise routine of "covers on, covers off" this takes up much of the night. I then lay in bed convincing myself that sleep is really overrated, as I listen to my husband snore. You know, if I could sleep I think I know what I would dream about...wishing I could borrow my husband's testicles because he seems to be able to sleep through everything.

