There are numerous reasons why people lose their temper but they all stem from one common element--anger that becomes so overpowering that all emotional control is lost. I do not lose my temper often, not because I do not get angry, but because I hate losing control of anything in my life, especially my emotions.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/nancys-world"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-1734" alt="baby-temper" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/nancys-world/files/2015/07/baby-temper-195x300.jpeg" width="156" height="240" /></a>
Most of the time after losing my temper I feel embarrassed by the fact that I could not reel in my emotions. Losing my temper only feels good for a very short time because I could blow off steam, but it rarely benefits the situation at hand. There was one time, however, that my outburst caused my son and I to have a special moment.

I do not tolerate anyone slamming a door in anger. I have 2 children, both who learned at a young age that this behavior was not acceptable. If a door was slammed, I would tell them that they obviously do not know how to open or close it properly and that they would have to practice 20 times so that they could learn. I am pretty certain that each of my children only slammed a door a couple of times when they were young.

One day I was really stressed about something. I remember going upstairs and looking into my high school son's room and all I could see was a mess. Clothes all over, dirty dishes, I could not even see the carpeting.I had asked him to clean his room for a couple days yet a tornado going through his room could only improve it. Suddenly I just lost it. I yelled and I may even stomped my feet and then I did the unthinkable...I slammed his door.

I made it down the stairs when I hear him yell down...Mom, you obviously do not know how to open and close a door. Please come up here and practice by doing it 20 times. I looked up at him, thought for a second, and I realized that I too should have the same consequences for my poor behavior. I went upstairs, opened and closed the door 20 times, we both laughed, and he preceded to clean his room. We both learned an important lesson that day all because of my lack of emotional control. He learned how to defuse a situation and I learned that my children actually listen to me preach and that I must practice what I preach.

